Ι myself‚ though long engaged in the preparation of this edition, thought at first that the two tractates on Space and Time were merely side- issues that might have been lopped off from Wyclif's philosophy without disadvantage to the whole. But on further consideration my opinion has been very much modified. His theory of Time and Space appears to me now as a logical result, partly of his Realism, partly of his doctrine concerning maxima and minima,· and this same theory is, I think, the root from which his doctrines on the Eucharist necessarily sprang. lt is thus essentially linked with his fundamental doctrines; but it is at the same time a link, indissolubly connecting them with the further develop- ments of his theological ideas.
